The following example (https://godbolt.org/z/54ze7P) has an unnecessary copy of `_1`:
```rust
fn should_opt(_1: bool) -> () {
    debug input => _1;                   // in scope 0 at ./example.rs:1:15: 1:20
    let mut _0: ();                      // return place in scope 0 at ./example.rs:1:28: 1:28
    let _2: bool;                        // in scope 0 at ./example.rs:2:9: 2:10
    scope 1 {
        debug x => _2;                   // in scope 1 at ./example.rs:2:9: 2:10
    }

    bb0: {
        StorageLive(_2);                 // scope 0 at ./example.rs:2:9: 2:10
        _2 = _1;                         // scope 0 at ./example.rs:2:13: 2:18
        _0 = const ();                   // scope 0 at ./example.rs:1:28: 3:2
        StorageDead(_2);                 // scope 0 at ./example.rs:3:1: 3:2
        return;                          // scope 0 at ./example.rs:3:2: 3:2
    }
}
```

I would have expected `_2 = _1` to be eliminated in the optimized MIR, as it appears unused besides storage markers.
